title: Want To Buy:  Riffle for a Monument
postcontent:
I am a disabled Marine Veteran, with many friends who didn't make it back. This past Memorial Day, as I shed my tears for my fallen brothers, I decided that I was going to build a memorial to them at my home here in Belfair. 

I am looking for any riffles that I can use for this purpose. They can be old, non functioning riffles too. I'm never going to shoot them. They are just going to be encases outside in a very peaceful and beautiful spot of honor to them. If you might have a riffle or two you could donate, I'd be very appreciative. I know it's a long shot.

One last thing though: I can't drive or really leave my house. My disabilities make me pretty much home bound. I know it's a lot to ask for donated riffles, then ask for delivery too, but like I said, I know it's a long shot. 

I don't ever want to forget my fellow Marines who died or who have been wounded in service to our country. This is in some small way going to pay tribute to them, while keeping them in the front of my mind (vs the back of my mind), and will be for my kids and neighbors to come by and remember the fallen as well. Though we never should need a small monument to remember, but this is just what I felt I have to do.

title: For Sale:  Like New Dueck Defense RTS 45 Degree Rapid Transition Sights AR-15
postcontent:
Like new, I had these for 3 months and never had a chance to shoot my AR with them mounted,  selling the set for $120 obo

 For AR-15 / M16 type rifles, optical sights provide superior performance at longer ranges, but iron sights can be more effective for close-range engagements. However, attaching an optical sight either prevents the use of iron sights or results in a setup that produces a front sight "shadow" on the optical image, and/or results in problematic transitions from optical to backup iron sights. Not anymore. Dueck Defense Rapid Transition Sights (RTS) provide shooters with the quickest possible transition between longer- and closer-range target acquisition, greatly increasing their efficiency and effectiveness in battle and competition. Designed by Barry Dueck Director of SureFire's Suppressor Division and a top 3-Gun shooter these sights mount directly to a weapon's Picatinny rail, offset from center by approximately 45°. This unique offset position makes transitioning from optical to iron sights simply a matter of quickly canting the weapon with your wrists and locking on to the target. There's no removing a hand from the weapon or making a manual adjustment, and no cluttered field of vision or iron sights blocking the optical sight. Just smooth, quick transitions that could mean the difference between winning or losing a competition, or more importantly a gunfight.

Up for sale is a Winchester WT-631C 15-45X60 Spotting Scope with Hard Case, lens covers, and soft carrying case.

I'd be selling this scope for at least $100, except for two reasons:  First, the tripod and mounting foot is not included.  Second, while at the range last year, another shooter's spent casing from his mini-14 struck the scope, and make a crack that appears from about the 9 o'clock to the 11 o'clock position in the view.  That crack is completely inconsequential to the function of the scope, and I continued using it at the range as recently as last week.

Unfortunately, as this scope does not meet my needs for shooting beyond 200 yards, I bought another spotting scope, and no longer need this one.

The bottom photo shows the crack as well as the shoreline of an island about 1 mile away.

This scope has served me well, and for the shooter who shoots 200 yards and under, the scope will save a lot of walking back and forth to and from the target to see your bullet holes.

title: For Sale:  TWO (2) Galco SR-22 +3 followers
postcontent:
This new slicker follower will allow you to carry 3 additional rounds in your 10 round SR22 mag. It works with any SR22 base plate and reuses your stock magazine spring. Zero feed issues just more bullets per mag at the same size. The only drawback is you loose your side tab on the body of the mag, (which locks the slide back on the last round) but it will lock back on the follower on the last round to let you know it's empty, on most pistols, some ammo brands will not allow this due to slide speed. The upside is the new material is slicker than stock and you won't need the tab to aid in loading anymore.


Not for sale in CA, CT, MA, NY, HI or anywhere else your banned from more than 10 rounds.

title: For Sale:  Taurus PT22 Pistol
postcontent:
Taurus PT22 Semiauto 9 round pistol. Made in USA
With 50 rounds of .22 ammo.
Call REDACTED
The PT22 is a .22LR semi-automatic pistol produced by Taurus and features an 8+1 round capacity magazine. The PT22 is often viewed as a Taurus copy of the Beretta 21 Bobcat due to having a similar "tip up" barrel. In fact this small pistol is very different in design and function from the Beretta. The PT22 is a cast steel frame and slide, manufactured in Florida, USA. It has a spur-less hammer, and a long but smooth double action only (DAO) trigger. The "tip up" barrel is useful in that the first round may be chambered directly into the barrel, and the operator does not have to "pull back" or "rack" the slide. Retracting the slide is difficult due to the heavy spring required in this blow-back action. The grip feel of the PT22 is "fat", and fills a normal-sized hand. This width may make the PT22 difficult for some smaller handed people to hold comfortably. The function and reliability of the PT22 is passable, with occasional failures to feed (but fewer than most Beretta 21s). The Taurus PT22 is able to fire most .22LR cartridges, including CCI Stingers.

title: For Sale:  2009 Hoyt Katera XL
postcontent:
I am selling my Hoyt Katera XL. This bow is a 27.5" draw and adjustable between 60-70 lbs. I bought this bow new in 2009 and it has been awesome. New Winner's Choice strings and cables from Diamond Archery this year. No cam lean. This bow is rated at 330 fps and shoots like a dream. It Is An Absolute Tack Driver!

This  bow draws a tad long.  I am really a 29" draw and this one pulls more like a 28.25".  I usually prefer a little shorter draw for stability.  The current set up would be perfect for a person drawing 28" - 28.5".  This cam is non adjustable which is part of the reason the Z3 cam is one of Hoyt's all time best.  A new upper cam can be purchased for $50-75 online for any draw length.

The price listed includes the bow, stabilizer, peep, quick quiver (three arrow) and string silencers.

I have a spot-hogg Hunter sight (pre wrap) on it now, which I bought for $200. This sight is top of the line as it is virtually indestructable and micro adjustable including 3rd axis adjustments. It hasn't slipped from zero once. I would include this for $50

The bow also has a QAD ultra rest - hd pro series rest. I just added this rest before last deer season ($140). It is the most accurate, quietest rest on the market and if it goes with the bow, I'll just have to buy the same one for my next bow. I'll include this rest for $80 if you want it. Otherwise I am more than happy to keep it.

This bow is much better than all of the mid line bows you can buy at Cabelas or Gander right now for a similar price. It is just as fast, quieter, more accurate and will last longer.
